05677nam a22007815i 9780231547437DE-B159720210526051534.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||210526t20202019nyu    fo  d z      eng d  a2019019479  a97802315474377 a10.7312/asph187722doi  a(DE-B1597)545466  a(OCoLC)1132424112  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  anyucUS-NY00aHV6439.U7bA837 2019 7aSOC0260302bisacsh1 aAspholm, Roberto, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aViews from the Streets :bThe Transformation of Gangs and Violence on Chicago's South Side /cRoberto Aspholm. 1aNew York, NY : bColumbia University Press, c[2020] 4c©2019  a1 online resource  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aStudies in Transgression00tFrontmatter -- tCONTENTS -- tACKNOWLEDGMENTS -- tIntroduction -- tChapter One. The Shattering of Chicago’s Black Street Gangs -- tChapter Two. From Street Organizations to Cliques: Black Street Gangs in Chicago Today -- tChapter Three. The Anatomy of Contemporary Gang Violence in Chicago -- tChapter Four. Understanding the Persistence of Gangs and Violence in Chicago -- tChapter Five. A Critical Appraisal of Violence Prevention Failures -- tConclusion. Reducing Gang Violence from the Streets Up -- tAPPENDIX: NOTES ON POSITIONALITY, THE POLITICS OF REPRESENTATION, AND RESEARCH METHODOLOGY -- tA PARTIAL GLOSSARY OF CHICAGO GANG SLANG -- tNOTES -- tBIBLIOGRAPHY -- tINDEX0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aChicago has long served as a symbol of urban pathology in the public imagination. The city’s staggering levels of violence and entrenched gang culture occupy a central place in the national discourse, yet remain poorly understood and are often stereotyped. Views from the Streets explains the dramatic transformation of black street gangs on Chicago’s South Side during the early twenty-first century, shedding new light on why gang violence persists and what might be done to address it.Drawing on years of community work and in-depth interviews with gang members, Roberto R. Aspholm describes in vivid detail the internal rebellions that shattered the city’s infamous corporate-style African American street gangs. He explores how, in the wake of these uprisings, young gang members have radically refashioned gang culture and organization on Chicago’s South Side, rejecting traditional hierarchies and ideologies and instead embracing a fierce ethos of personal autonomy that has made contemporary gang violence increasingly spontaneous and unregulated. In calling attention to the historical context of these issues and to the elements of resistance embedded in Chicago’s contemporary gang culture, Aspholm challenges conventional views of gang members as inherently pathological. He critically analyzes highly touted “universal” violence prevention strategies, depicting street-level realities to illuminate why they have ultimately failed to reduce levels of bloodshed. An unprecedented analysis of the nature and meaning of gang violence, Views from the Streets proposes an alternative framework for addressing the seemingly intractable issues of inequality, despair, and violence in Chicago.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 26. Mai 2021) 0aCriminal justice, Administration ofzIllinoiszChicago. 0aGangszIllinoiszChicago. 0aHomicidezIllinoiszChicago. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Sociology / Urban.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertCUP eBook-Package Package 2019z978311066221408iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertCUP eBook-Package Pilot Project 2019z978311065195908iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2020 Englishz978311070471608iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2020z978311